ralism. One asks whether, following Keynes and Hayek, Polanyi’s ideas will shape the twenty-first century. Some clarify, for the meaning of money as a fictitious commodity. Others resolve difficulties in understanding the building blocks of Polanyi's thought: fictitious commodities, the double movement, the United States' exceptional development, the reality of society, and socialism as freedom in a complex society. And yes others explore how Polanyi sheds light on income inequality, world systems theory, comparative political economy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCapitalism. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aDouble Movement.  aKarl Polanyi.  aThe Reality of Society.  afascism.  afictitious commodities.  afreedom.  ainequality.  aneoliberalism.  asocialism.1 aBlock, Fred, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrie, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDesai, Radhika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDesai, Radhika, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHudson, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLacher, Hannes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevitt, Kari Polanyi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevitt, Kari Polanyi, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNakayama, Chikako, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeck, Jamie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRotstein, Abraham, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSomers, Margaret R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThomasberger, Claus, econtributor.4ctb